TwitterQA results

J. Herrera, D. Parra, B. Poblete

October 13, 2015

Statistical Analysis of the results for paper submitted to Knowledge-Based Systems Journal: “Q&A Retrieval for Streaming-Microblogging Platforms”.

Read data file:

# results-twitterqa-v3.csv is just another name for results-twitterqa.csv
ranking_results_df <- read.csv(file='results-twitterqa-v3.csv',head=TRUE , sep=',')

ranking_results_df$RANK <- factor(ranking_results_df$RANK, levels = c('cos','singleTweet','url','replies','favorite','favoriteAsker','askerFeedback','sentiment','sentimentAsker','favorite_url','askerFeedback_url','sentiment_url','askerFeedback_cos'))

Get mean, S.E. per ranking method

library(dplyr)
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 3.1.2
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
stats_by_rank_method <- ranking_results_df %>%
group_by(RANK) %>%
summarise(
    mean_MRR = round(mean(MRR),3),
    se_MRR = round(sd(MRR)/sqrt(n()),3),
    mean_nDCG = round(mean(nDCG),3),
    se_nDCG = round(sd(nDCG)/sqrt(n()),3),
    mean_P.1 = round(mean(P.1),3),
    se_P.1 = round(sd(P.1)/sqrt(n()),3),
    mean_P.5 = round(mean(P.5),3),
    se_P.5 = round(sd(P.5)/sqrt(n()),3)    
    ) %>% 
    select(RANK, mean_MRR, se_MRR, mean_nDCG, se_nDCG, mean_P.1, se_P.1, mean_P.5, se_P.5)

We need an additional function to plot the 4 metrics with a common legend require(gridExtra)

require(gridExtra)
## Loading required package: gridExtra
## Loading required package: grid
grid_arrange_shared_legend <- function(...) {
    plots <- list(...)
    g <- ggplotGrob(plots[[1]] + theme(legend.position="left"))$grobs
    legend <- g[[which(sapply(g, function(x) x$name) == "guide-box")]]
    lheight <- sum(legend$height)
    lwidth <- sum(legend$width)
    grid.arrange(
        do.call(arrangeGrob, lapply(plots, function(x)
            x + theme(legend.position="none"))),
        legend,
        ncol = 2 ,
        #heights = unit.c(unit(1, "npc") - lheight, lheight)
        #widths = unit.c(unit(1, "npc") - lwidth, lwidth)
        widths = unit.c( unit(0.85,"npc") , unit(0.15, "npc") )
        )
}

and finally produce the plot (for space limitation, this plot is not in the paper)

grid_arrange_shared_legend(g1, g2, g3,g4, ncol=2)

Now, to produce the plot in the article:

  1. Subset the original dataframe and calculate the MRR ratio
rr_cos <- ranking_results_df[ranking_results_df$RANK == 'cos',]
names(rr_cos) <- c("id",   "RANKcos", "MRRcos",  "nDCGcos", "P.1cos",  "P.5cos") 
rmerged <- merge(ranking_results_df, rr_cos, by='id' )
names(rmerged)
##  [1] "id"      "RANK"    "MRR"     "nDCG"    "P.1"     "P.5"     "RANKcos"
##  [8] "MRRcos"  "nDCGcos" "P.1cos"  "P.5cos"
rmerged2 <-  rmerged[rmerged$MRRcos > 0.165,]
rmerged2$MRRratio <- (rmerged2[rmerged2$MRRcos > 0.165,]$MRR)/(rmerged2[rmerged2$MRRcos > 0.165,]$MRRcos)

rmerged2$RANKmrr <- reorder(rmerged2$RANK, rmerged2$MRRratio)
  1. GGplot it
ggplot(rmerged2[!(rmerged2$RANK %in% c('cos','singleTweet')), ], aes(x=RANKmrr, y=(MRRratio) ) ) + stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "point") + stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "text", aes(label=paste(100*round((..y..-1),3),'%') ),vjust=-0.8 ) + stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "line") + stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_boot, geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2) + coord_flip() + xlab('Ranking') + ylab('MRR ~ performance ratio vs. baseline (rank_cos)') +theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_text(size=18), axis.title.x=element_text(size=15), axis.title.y=element_text(size=15), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray80", size = 0.8, linetype="dashed"), panel.grid.major.x = element_blank())

Statistical tests

Data non-normally distributed, for MRR for instance

hist.data.frame(ranking_results_df[,c('MRR','nDCG','P.5')])

baseline comparisons: rank_cos vs. rank_singleTweet

wilcox.test(ranking_results_df[ranking_results_df$RANK == 'cos',]$MRR,ranking_results_df[ranking_results_df$RANK == 'singleTweet',]$MRR,paired=TRUE)
